04343nam a22006015i 9780822398028DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223980287 a10.1515/97808223980282doi  a(DE-B1597)553571  a(OCoLC)1229161812  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR878.S317bC64 1996 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a823/.80935382201 aCohen, William A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSex Scandal :bThe Private Parts of Victorian Fiction /cWilliam A. Cohen. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Sex, Scandal, and the Novel -- t2 Manual Conduct in Great Expectations -- t3 Privacy and Publicity in the Victorian Sex Scandal -- t4 Schadenfreude in The Mill on the Floss -- t5 Trollope's Trollop -- t6 Indeterminate Wilde -- tAfterword -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNever has the Victorian novel appeared so perverse as it does in these pages-and never his its perversity seemed so fundamental to its accomplishment. Whether discussing George Eliot's lesbian readers, Anthony Trollope's whorish heroines, or Charles Dickens's masturbating characters, William A. Cohen's study explodes the decorum of mainstream nineteenth-century fiction. By viewing this fiction alongside the most alarming public scandals of the day, Cohen exposes both the scandalousness of this literature and its sexiness.Scandal, then as now, makes public the secret indiscretions of prominent people, engrossing its audience in salacious details that violate the very code of propriety it aims to enforce. In narratives ranging from Great Expectations to the Boulton and Park sodomy scandal of 1870-71, from Eliot's and Trollope's novels about scandalous women to Oscar Wilde's writing and his trials for homosexuality, Cohen shows how, in each instance, sexuality appears couched in coded terms. He identifies an assortment of cunning narrative techniques used to insinuate sex into Victorian writing, demonstrating that even as such narratives air the scandalous subject, they emphasize its unspeakable nature.Written with an eye toward the sex scandals that still whet the appetites of consumers of news and novels, this work is suggestive about our own modes of imagining sexuality today and how we arrived at them. Sex Scandal will appeal to scholars and general readers interested in Victorian literature, the history of sexuality, gender studies, nineteenth-century Britain, and gay, lesbian, and queer studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aScandals in literature. 0aSex in literature. 0aSex scandalszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398028zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398028.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles